===Etymology===
First attested in the 17th century, noun use of 5th century {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|oxymorum|oxymōrum|pos=adj|lang=la}}, neut. nom. form of {{term|oxymorus|oxymōrus|pos=adj|lang=la}},<ref name="L+S">{{R:L&S|1=oxymōrus|2=oxymorus}}</ref> from {{etyl|grc|en}} {{term|ὀξύμωρος|||lang=grc}}, compound of {{term|ὀξύς||sharp, keen, pointed|lang=grc}}<ref>{{R:LSJ|1=o)cu/s2|w=ὀξύς}}</ref> (English {{term|oxy-|lang=en}}, as in {{term|oxygen|lang=en}}) + {{term|μωρός||dull, stupid, folly|lang=grc}}<ref>{{R:LSJ|1=mwro/s|w=μωρός}}</ref> (English {{term|moron||stupid person|lang=en}}). Literally “sharp-dull”, "keen-stupid" or "pointed folly"<ref name="LSJ">{{R:LSJ|1=o)cu/mwros|w=ὀξύμωρος}}</ref> – itself an '''oxymoron''', hence [[autological]]; compare {{term|sophomore|lit=wise fool|lang=en}}, influenced by similar analysis. The compound form {{m|grc|ὀξύμωρον}} is not found in the extant Ancient Greek sources.<ref>OED: [http://dictionary.oed.com.ezproxy.sfpl.org/cgi/entry/50168789]</ref>

