===Noun===
{{en-noun|s|oxymora}}

# A [[figure of speech]] in which two words with opposing meanings are used together intentionally for effect.
# {{context|general|lang=en}} A [[contradiction in terms]].

====Usage notes====
* Historically, an {{term||oxymoron}} was "a {{term|paradox}} with a point",<ref>Jebb, Sir Richard (1900). ''[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:1999.04.0023:text=comm:commline=74&highlight=o%29cu%2Fmwron Sophocles: The Plays and Fragments, with critical notes, commentary, and translation in English prose. Part III: The Antigone]''. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press.</ref> where the contradiction seems absurd at first glance, and yet is deliberate, its purpose being to underscore a point or to draw attention to a concealed point. The modern usage of {{term||oxymoron}} as a synonym for the simpler [[contradiction in terms]] is considered incorrect by some speakers and writers, and is perhaps best avoided in certain contexts.<ref name="L+S" /><ref name="LSJ" /> (See also the [[w:oxymoron|Wikipedia article]].)

